  "reykjavik.D.agenda.0.text": "Smooth transport in Reykjavík through investment in infrastructure, public transit and cycling lanes — freedom to choose your mode of travel.",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.0.title": "Freedom and choice in transport",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.1.text": "All neighbourhoods designed so residents can reach essential shops and services within a 15–20 minute walk.",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.1.title": "15-minute neighbourhoods",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.2.text": "Expand preschool places, workplace childcare and subsidies for parents who choose home care after parental leave.",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.2.title": "Diverse post-parental-leave options",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.3.text": "Clear performance targets and standardised assessment; position Reykjavík's primary schools among Europe's best.",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.3.title": "Primary education excellence",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.4.text": "Increase land supply and promote owner-occupied housing; new neighbourhoods in Geldinganes, Keldnaland and Úlfarsárdalur.",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.4.title": "Housing in household ownership",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.5.text": "Expand Elliðaárdalur as Reykjavík's 'Central Park'; more heated pathways powered by clean energy.",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.5.title": "Green spaces and environment",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.6.text": "Reduce city councillors from 23 to 15; lower commercial property taxes; sell municipal enterprises operating in competitive markets.",
  "reykjavik.D.agenda.6.title": "More efficient city governance",
  "reykjavik.D.list.1.bio": "Hildur Björnsdóttir was born on 11 June 1986 in San Francisco and raised in Hafnarfjörður. She is a lawyer with a BA in political science and a master's degree in law from the University of Iceland. She has served on Reykjavík City Council since 2018 and has been the leader of the Independence Party in Reykjavík since 2022.",
