  "reykjavik.F.agenda.0.text": "A society where everyone can live with dignity, security and equal opportunities; \"quality of life is not the exclusive right of a few\".",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.0.title": "People first",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.1.text": "Development of affordable housing and small flats in cooperation with social institutions; opposed to over-densification.",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.1.title": "Affordable housing",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.2.text": "Substantially reduce waiting lists; explore more diverse and cost-effective ways to increase preschool places.",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.2.title": "Preschool issues",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.3.text": "Improve traffic flow for all modes of transport; the system must work for those who depend on cars.",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.3.title": "Transport justice",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.4.text": "Emphasis on quality of education, improved reading instruction, individualised support and student wellbeing.",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.4.title": "Primary schools",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.5.text": "Ensure carefree later years and dignity in old age.",
  "reykjavik.F.agenda.5.title": "Elderly care",
  "reykjavik.F.list.1.bio": "Guðmundur Ingi Þóroddsson was born in 1974 and is the chair of Afstaða, the association of prisoners and former prisoners. He spent a total of 16 years in prison and has since devoted himself to campaigning for prisoners’ rights. He works for the Welfare Department of the City of Reykjavík and leads the Flokkur fólksins list in Reykjavík.",
  "reykjavik.F.list.1.interests.0": "Prisoners’ rights and rehabilitation",
